##A war for women

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

Liang Yu said that when the epidemic came, she was very afraid, every day to think of themselves, will be infected? Does that mean you can't go out? When she launched the Sisterhood Epidemic, Delivering 338317 pairs of safety pants and 202209 pairs of disposable underwear to front-line female doctors, and when she actually did something for other women and provided real help, she saw that life was different.

By Lai Yuxuan

Editor | locust tree

The sound of oblivion

When her period came, little bear, a girl living in Beijing, decided to go online and buy some sanitary napkins. The usual big brand, usually can be delivered within 24 hours, today, the merchant told her that there is no stock. It was February 7th, and the epidemic wasn't getting any better. Little bear suddenly thought, Beijing's situation is so bad, the epidemic center of Hubei, especially has been closed to the third week of Wuhan, what will be? She opened her microblog and searched for "epidemic areas" and "Sanitary Napkins" to see if anyone had discussed the issue. She found Liang Yu.

That night, Liang Yu, a 24-year-old Shanghai girl, asked on Weibo how front-line medical workers could solve the problem of menstruation? Do they have enough sanitary pads and safety pants? A few days ago, Liang Yu saw a video of Wuhan medical staff taking off their protective clothing. It took up to 30 minutes in 27 steps and 12 times to disinfect their hands. The paramedic on the scene is female. She therefore thought, once the menstrual cycle, such a complex wear off process, how to deal with the issue of female doctors and Nurses Sanitary Napkin replacement? In order to save consumption of protective clothing, women will not choose to Change Sanitary Napkins?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Medical staff demonstrate the process of taking off protective clothing image source lychee video

Liang Yu is going to donate some sanitary pads and safety pants. To get them to Wuhan as quickly as possible, merchants in Hubei Province are the best bet. Taobao shop one by one to search, see the delivery is in Hubei, to ask, "Do you have inventory? "? I'M GONNA buy a lot of them.". The first one I found was Jie Ting, a local sanitary napkin brand in Hubei Province. They know the idea of Liang Yu, spent three times wages to ask workers to come back to work overtime, the inventory are transferred out, but also insisted on not the money of Liang Yu. With supplies, Liang Yu asked a friend of the hospital in Wuhan, I heard to donate peace of mind pants, the other side was very surprised, "there are people donated this? "? What we need, what we need. "Two days later, the Sanitary Napkins arrived at the hospital, and Liang Yu thought, what about other hospitals? So on Weibo, she posted the query, which had 270,000 followers and had about 100 retweets each, and this one had more than 1,600.

Suddenly, countless private messages poured in, mostly from front-line medical women: They had applied to the leadership and had not been given Sanitary Napkins for several days; they did not eat or drink for eight hours, did not urinate, did not dare to go to the toilet; the head nurse paid for diapers herself; Get Sanitary Towel also reluctant to use, first to the patient; no physiological supplies, with plastic film shoulder for a while; only diapers can be used, blood and urine are mixed together... support Hubei medical teams from all over the more difficult, hurry to come, i didn't have time to prepare this. Hubei is humid, even the rain and snow, a pair of underwear are not dry. There are no clothes to change, no clothes to take out after the quarantine zone, and many female doctors even choose not to wear underwear, can only wear blood protective clothing to walk around.

Based on the private messages, Liang wrote another Weibo Post, which was retweeted 17,000 times, calling for more attention to frontline women's health care. She received more private messages from frontline women's doctors, asking for help, wanting to talk to her, and being cautiously asked if she could serve five people first, and not much. Liang Yu felt sad and sorrowful. That same day, February 7, Xiao Xiong found Liang Yu, want to do this with her to the medical women sent Sanitary Napkins work. What they do is trivial and repetitive: They make phone calls. Call the hospital, ask if you need safety pants; call the brand, ask if there is stock; call logistics, ask if there is a fleet.

Calling the hospital was the first step. Following the online list of hospitals to solicit donations and the information for help released by the Health Commission, they started from more than 20 hospitals in Wuhan and then found hospitals in other cities in Hubei Province, calling one by one. Rejection is the norm. The most common expression is, "hospitals need masks and protective clothing, not supplies. ". They gradually discovered that men were more likely to say no if they answered the phone. They do not know what safety pants are, think and diapers are not too different, and even some people asked, "safety pants men can also use? "? The only man who responded quickly to their donation was a director of the Xiaogan City headquarters, who graduated from Peking University as a social worker. Later, Ms. Liang learned that before she started the campaign, Ms. Jie had made donations to two major hospitals in Wuhan, both of which were rejected on the grounds that they were not needed.

Little Bear found that the female voice was being drowned out bit by bit. The demand is there, but some women are too embarrassed to express it because they think the menstrual cycle is private, and others express it, but when the person they turn to doesn't pass it on to the purchasing department, or the department may decide that these needs are less important, and the voices that aren't so strong are weakened. During the epidemic period, the demand of hospitals, medical supplies must be in the first place, women's demand for physiological supplies is also being suppressed.

What Liang Yu and Xiao Xiong have to do, is to find those hidden behind, female voices.

They changed their interrogation techniques. At first, they asked, "we have some safety pants we'd like to donate. Do you need them? "? " then they asked, "we have a lot of safety pants. How many female employees do you have? What's your address? Instead of giving a choice, the caller was prompted to realize, "we have female employees here, and we can ask them what they want. " If they are still rejected, Liang Yu and Xiao Xiong will struggle one last time, "Is there a female staff member near you? Can I speak to her, please? "

Using the numbers from the calls, Liang and Xiong got a glimpse of just how large a group first line women's health care is: Wuhan Tongji Hospital, with more than 5,000 Female Health Care Workers; Wuhan Union Medical College General Hospital, with about 5,700 workers; Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, with about 1,300 workers; Wuhan Hankou Hospital, about 600 people; Wuhan Tongji Hospital, Zhongfa Xincheng district, about 1,000 people; Xiaogan, about 16,600 people... They contacted hospitals, female medical staff accounted for 60%-70% , some maternity hospitals more than 80% . As of February 7, none of these hospitals had received donations of sanitary napkins or other physiological supplies.

On February 8, Liang Yu started to form a team of volunteers for the "sister relief operation against the epidemic" to provide menstrual assistance to frontline female health care workers. She thought it was time to do something for the sisters.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Volunteer team of "sisters in the war" delivers supplies to the interviewees in the picture

Cry And fight

The idea of fundraising came to me in the first tweet. She was approached by a group of fans who wanted to raise money with her, but she quickly learned that as an individual, she was not eligible for public donations; she wondered how much it would cost to get a few close friends to help fund something like a Sanitary Napkin? But the numbers made her realize that it wasn't something she could do on her own or with a few friends.

She came up with the idea of raising money in the name of the team, and the first thing she had to do was find a qualified foundation. Through one of the volunteers, a Peking University graduate, Liang found the Soul Mountain Foundation, founded by Peking University Alumni, who were willing to help raise money for the project. The amount raised is expected to be more than 2.26 million yuan for the purchase of 100,000 safety pants, more than 100,000 disposable underwear, including 100,000 logistics costs and 50,000 emergency expenses.

2.26 million is not a small number, but it does not cover many female health care workers. Six Safety Pants for one person, 100,000 safety pants for 16,700 people. 20 pairs of disposable underwear for one person, 100,000 pairs for only 5,000 people. The $2.26 million worth of safety pants and disposable underwear is less than a month's supply. Liang Yu remembers that there were male volunteers on the team at the time to remind them how to give only three days'worth? At least four days. She felt powerless to reach more women, only by the lowest standards.

On Feb. 11, the day people interviewed Liang, they launched a fund raising campaign. Every five minutes, Liang Yu opened the fundraising page and looked at the progress bar of the amount raised.

Sal, the publicist, was anxious, too. SEAH is studying at a university in Shenzhen and has set up a small company specializing in sex education. She's been focusing on the science of female physiology. In a survey, she found that when the Wenchuan County earthquake emergency relief, the distribution list almost no sanitary napkins and other physiological supplies. After the outbreak of pneumonia, she wondered, could this neglect also occur in the fight against the epidemic? She found Liang Yu on Weibo and joined them.

Seah and her team spent a day and a half writing an article they wanted to publish the day after the event. They changed it again and again, for fear that it would not be clearly written, and for fear that the common man's fund raising would be quiet, and in order to be seen by more people, she made a point of calling a few self media numbers and asking them to forward it.

Seah and Liang Yu's worry was unnecessary. Wake up, fund-raiser's over. In 13 hours, they raised $2,355,051.96. SEAR's unpublished article was pruned and turned into a progress bulletin.

It was Feb. 12, and Liang and Seah found that they didn't need to call the hospitals anymore. Many of the hospitals approached them for help, as well as hospitals in Henan and Hunan. In addition to the paramedics, female police officers also came to inquire about Sanitary Napkins. Information Help Group volunteers, add people to the phone once crashed. There were already 165 hospitals in the pool that day, and the demand for women's care at those 165 hospitals alone far exceeded the amount of supplies that could be raised in the first round of donations, they had to temporarily shut down the hospital's docking bay.

It's an indescribably complex feeling. With so many days of persistence, they dig out of the cover, the real voice of women, but also feel powerless. Such a jumble of calls for attention means that this is not just the plight of Hubei, not only the plight of health care workers, the country in the front line of the fight against the epidemic may be caught in a heated battle with the menstrual cycle.

Her dream in life is to co-ordinate a women's rights NGO project at the age of 50. Unexpectedly, at the age of 24, she realized in action. Caught off guard, she was pushed into a position, "actually, it pains me. "Liang Yu told people. Busy and tired is certain, the information and urgent need to urge them, but also to face some unfriendly voices.

For example, a media interview asked Liang Yu, "is there any obstacle because of the sensitive word 'menstruation' ? "? "It was also a girl. Liang Yu did not understand when "menstruation" became a sensitive word, and even women themselves should be ashamed of it?

Still others question why health care workers don't buy their own pads? Why can't you just suck it up? Why can't you order online? Little Bear felt very angry, "this is completely 'why not eat meat MINCE' IDEA! "! After the closure of the city, it was very difficult for ordinary citizens in Wuhan to get out of their residential areas, not to mention the fact that these first-line medical and nursing staff, under the circumstances of a sharp increase in the number of medical consultations, could hardly sleep and did not have time to buy Sanitary Napkins. At the same time, a large number of shops were closed and supplies were scarce, couriers are hard to get around. They just have to live with it.

Liang Yu heard many stories from the front line of Women's health care, but also heard many let her angry voice. Some she can share, she posts on twitter to discuss, and some she can't talk about, she keeps to herself.

That anger, it's a long time coming. From an early age, Liang Yu felt that she was a "normal person, " and that women should be able to say the same things and do the same things as men without thinking too much about gender. "I lived my life the way everyone told me to live mine, but as I got older, I realized I couldn't live that way anymore. Just because I'm a woman, I can't live like a normal person, and I have a big problem with that. For example, a man might think that a child is not his child if he does not take his last name, but I am a woman, and if I do, I have a problem. Every time I say the same thing and do the same thing as a man, someone starts yelling at me. "

One night, she couldn't take it anymore. She called a counseling hotline and cried for an hour. After the crying, I thought, "well, let's just keep fighting. "

Female doctors and nurses at Wuhan Central Hospital receive donations from "sister wars" . Photo source: respondents

Hit the road

Wuhan Girl Flute has a car, the driver is her mother. Dizi can drive, but she doesn't have a driver's license. When she joined the Wuhan Volunteer Team, her mother followed her to deliver the goods. Other parents lock their children in their homes, leaving only their mothers, not only to lock them up, but to take them with them to Florida from the day of the blockade. Together, they have delivered alcohol masks, chicken, duck, fish and vegetables, and this time, Sanitary Napkins. Kazoo said, mom is very cool, heard is to send Sanitary Napkins, very calm and said, "yes, someone should have sent. ". "

Logistics is the most difficult part of the fundraising and donation process, as mentioned by the Sisterhood Team members.

Sanitary towels can not enter the list of medical supplies or goods in short supply, it can not enter the green channel of logistics, it is difficult to find logistics companies to undertake transport, can only rely on volunteers private cars. Sometimes it takes them a whole day to get to a hospital, or even days.

Some of the appeals and donations came from other cities in Hubei, where cross-city deliveries made finding a car even more difficult. If the Huanggang to pick up the driver, to be transferred from the warehouse in Wuhan, Sanitary Napkins back to Huanggang, the driver will have to face 14 days of isolation. Equivalent to a trip, people "lost" , the driver master has become an extremely precious, need to be careful use of consumption resources.

The need for help is also changing in real time. Docking group told "people" , often a hospital yesterday also need 5000 pieces of safety pants, contact today is not necessary, has been obtained from other channels of supplies. The forms for receiving donated materials are updated several times a day, but they often fail to keep up with the changes. The logistics team always has to wait until the last minute to find out whether or not they should leave today and where they are going. Even when the convoy arrives at the hospital, i realized I didn't need it anymore.

During the siege, the roads in Wuhan were treacherous. Warehouses are mostly in the suburbs, hospitals are in the city, and getting a pass from the suburbs to the city is a problem. A lot of roads are blocked, and sometimes the map doesn't show up until you get to one and you find a roadblock in between. All they could do was look around for the back roads. Even the path is uncertain. You don't need a pass at this intersection today, do you need it tomorrow? If you can get out of the neighborhood today, can you get out tomorrow? This pass will work today, will it work tomorrow? No one knows the answer.

The flute said, on the road, all depends on luck. After the siege, she and a dozen other young people set up a volunteer convoy, delivering vegetables, hairpins, alcohol, watering cans, 23 tons of sugar oranges and 30 tons of bananas. This is a group of subculture youth, DJ, Coser, photographer, graffiti youth, open video game city, do clothing shop, and motorcycle enthusiasts.

These days, they also help a small group of sisters to Deliver Sanitary Napkins. One day the task is heavy, a few boys worried, while researching how to put into the car, while marveling, "how can you girls need so many Sanitary Napkins? "? "

Kazoo is a bit surprised that they know so little about the female menstrual cycle. When she explained, the boys suddenly realized, "Oh, you don't only use one pill a month! "

The moment made a deep impression on flute. If these young men who are willing to help women carry sanitary Napkins know so little about the female menstrual cycle, how much do those middle-aged men who answer the phone at the hospital know about the female Menstrual Cycle? She suddenly felt a little understanding of the rejections. There is a need for more communication between the sexes.

25 boxes of safety pants in an SUV, 15 boxes in a hatchback. There was a weird twist to the boxes, but it didn't matter. On Feb. 17, Dizi and volunteers sent safety pants to 17 hospitals in Wuhan, and on Feb. 19, less than two hours later, they sent another 17.

As of 19 February, sanitary pads and safety pants had reached 44 hospitals, only 26 per cent of the 165 hospitals in the help pool had been completed. Kazoo and her pals are still flying, and they've found a new way to fit 25 cases of safety pants into a hatchback.

Everyone on the team talks about flutes in interviews. They all wondered, what is the flute made of? In Wuhan so difficult road conditions, on time to deliver all the goods, incredible. The flute did not feel so difficult, she said, they are sent to the Wuhan City Hospital, is still easy.

But what happens next? Neither does the flute. She was used to the early morning fireworks atmosphere in Wuhan, but after the city was closed, everything changed. The road was almost deserted, and the only busy places were pharmacies and supermarkets. She particularly likes to eat a shop of beef powder, one day delivery, she deliberately around the street, most of the store closed, bleak, suddenly saw a shop out of a plume of steam and smoke. I got closer and realized it wasn't the beef noodle shop she loved, but she wanted to cry.

On February 12, Dizi was entrusted by Liang Yu, ran out of the community, in Wuhan around to Hainan Medical Team Sisters to collect safety pants. She wore a neapolitan team scarf. She owned several Neapolitan scarves, the only one that had a cheer written on it, which she sang loudly after every win. Dizi felt that the song was about them, the women who fought for the women, "and as time goes by, they never leave, just like every other day, to defend the city. "

Dizi handed the safety pants and disposable underwear to the Hainan medical team

The power of sisters

The team's propaganda posters were originally pink, and Liang Yu objected. She wanted to use blue to represent the action. She wanted to take this opportunity to show everyone that a woman's color can also be blue. "Isn't Elsa from Frozen blue? That's a post-2000 girl's hero. Who says blue isn't for girls? There is no color that can represent a gender. "

The typeface is round, and Liang still objects. She wants no words to be curved, no pink, cute symbols. "Heart" on the point, she wanted to get a sword, thought or points, only to change into sanitary napkins. Everything that is presented and communicated has to be a woman's power.

Poster on "Sister Relief Campaign". The bottom photo shows the "sisters in the war and epidemic" team donating sanitary napkins to the Hubei Medical Aid team in Dushanzi District, Xinjiang

After the establishment of the organization, the Topic Tag, Liang Yu chose the sister war peace of mind action. At the time, Xiao Xiong was worried. She reminded Liang Yu to be careful. "Once our views and positions are exploited, guided and distorted, all our efforts to help our fellow women will be wasted. ". " She told Liang Yu, "there are some objections that can be ignored. We want to do something, you just do it, and you tell people exactly what you're doing. "

They all know how hard it was to get this far. Fifteen days ago, more than 60 volunteers in various locations were strangers, and 15 days later, most of them still didn't know each other's names, identities or faces, only that they were doing the same thing, to find the voice these first-line women should have.

Now the girls on the medical team are willing to call the volunteers "sisters" when they receive the goods. When the girls of the Dushanzi District medical team heard that anxin pants were coming, they trotted down the stairs with long red banners to greet them. There were only two boxes of safety pants, and they were right in the middle, and some of the girls were happily pulling up banners that said, "fight the epidemic, take responsibility. ". And then there's the doctor, who comes out in his Hazmat suit to receive his safety pants, and the first thing he says when he sees the volunteer is, "don't be afraid, you've just changed into a clean Hazmat suit, and you're not in the quarantine zone. ". Sign the paperwork, collect the shipment, say "thank you" , and get back to work. Liang Yu feels, it is the temperature of these women illuminates them, volunteer ability holds to go down bit by bit. "Call me a sister, and I'll call you a sister. "

Sisters, as the volunteer team calls each other. Kazoo liked the word, and she said she felt a connection she had never felt before, a strong connection between people. Se Ah sent Liang Yu a private letter for the first time. Both of them were polite. After you came and went, Liang Yu suddenly called out, "sister! From that moment on, Seah felt different. It was the first time she had ever been called a sister, and she felt empowered. Later, whenever a new member entered the group, seah would immediately shout, "sister! Can you help me with this? "The other responded warmly. Once, sal found out that a girl called "sister" for a few days was a boy.

Ab was one of the few men in charge of the sister war team, a "big brother" after the 1980s. He stayed home during the quarantine and stumbled upon the activity. At first, he just wanted to do something, but when he joined, he was "really, really impressed. ".

He managed the materials group and connected with the manufacturers. He felt that "four days' work was worth a month's work" . He was therefore surprised that these young girls were so pumped up that they worked ten hours a day without eating more than one meal, 24 hours, he's talking, he's got people on the line. "very brave, " he said of them, burning like a fire among the women, and setting him on fire.

As a male, part of the sisterhood, Ab felt it was also a male voice. He was willing to join them, to care for them, to understand their needs, their power. "It's not about the rise of women, " she said. "I think it's good that society treats them as equals. "

But it is women who understand women best. When we come as sisters, as women, we discover that there are things you don't have to say, that I understand, that I would do for you. "said little bear.

Liang Yu said, when the epidemic came, she was very afraid, every day to think of themselves, will be infected? Does that mean you can't go out? When she actually does something for other women, and offers real help, she sees that life is different. Every woman in action becomes alive, real and concrete. Liang wasn't sure whether being busy had made her forget her worries, or whether the women had allayed her fear of the virus. "Anyway, I don't feel so scared anymore. "

As of February 20, the campaign had collected and coordinated donations from frontline female health care workers in total: 338317 pairs of safety pants, 202209 pairs of disposable underwear, 2,880 sanitary napkins and 700 hand cream, covering 79 hospitals and medical teams with more than 60,000 people. The delivery of supplies continues. More groups, groups, brands, and individuals are jumping in. The China Women's Fund raised 40,000 packs of Sanitary Napkins to be shipped to Wuhan, and the Hengan Group pledged to donate 2.6 million Sanitary Napkins and 200,000 safety pants to Hubei every month until the epidemic is over... Liang Yu said, she knew that many of the medical teams that later sent out aid would pack the women's gear with safety pants and pads.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The donation situation of the "sister relief campaign" in Wuhan City is illustrated by the respondents

On February 19, neurofood, the public account of the sister wars volunteer team, posted an article explaining the situation facing front-line female health care, talking about menstrual blood and asking, "why is there a difference between high and low when it's blood? "? "

"We hope that in the wake of this epidemic, the normal physiological phenomena of women, who make up half of the population, will no longer be labelled as 'special' and menstruation will no longer be a physical shame. We don't have to talk about her every day, but hopefully the past that she can't talk about, that she can't talk about, is really the past. "At the end of the article, they said.

Liang Yu always remembers February 11 as a good day. Not only was the fundraising link finally up, but a female paramedic came to her and asked if she had any hand cream to donate? She thinks it's great that women can finally stop being so self-conscious and shy about asking for things. "It's OK, just say what women want. ". "

Haven't you seen enough?
